abstract: BRIDGEPORT, Conn., Aug. 31. -- William J. Bryan arrived here from New Haven shortly after 6 o'clock this evening, and was greeted by the largest crowd that has assembled in Bridgeport for many months. abstract: THERE came to an end two days ago a period that was probably the most remarkable in the history of the United States Military Academy at West Point. Brig. Gen. Albert L. Mills retired from the Superintendency on Friday, to be succeeded by Major Hugh L. Scott of the Fourteenth Cavalry. It had been eight years since Gen. Mills went to West Point, a mere Lieutenant of cavalry, named, by President McKinley.

abstract: ST. PETERSBURG, Sept. 1. -- Gen. Count Orloff, who attained considerable notoriety by the severity with which he suppressed the revolutionary disturbances in the Baltic Provinces, has agreed to replace Gen. Skallon as Governor General of Warsaw. The complete disarming of the population of Warsaw was made a condition of his acceptance, and last night's police raid at Warsaw was a step in carrying out this stipulation.

abstract: OYSTER BAY, L.I., Sept. 3. -- To this town to-day many pilgrims journeyed to worship at the shrine of power as exemplified in the big battleships. abstract: PARIS. -- A drama could be made out of the story of a grocer's marriage at Grenoble. He was seven and twenty, ambitious, and pleasing. He was introduced to a rich tradesman with a still buxom wife and a pretty daughter of 18 years. The young grocer's game was obvious. The surest way to win a fair bride and handsome portune was to propitiate his intended mother-in-law, and this he did only too well.

abstract: Magistrate Crane in the Tombs Court astonished three alleged pickpockets yesterday by committing them to the Tombs for forty-eight hours instead of setting them free, as they had expected. abstract: PUNKSUTAWNEY, Penn., Sept. 3. -- Two members of the State Constabulary are dead, one is dying, and two others are wounded as a result of a riot with Italians at Florence, a town seven miles from here, yesterday. abstract: The local trade is inclined to discount alarmists' reports of the metal famine from the Pittsburg district. abstract: The International Steam Pump Company's reports for the fiscal year ending March 31 were made public yesterday. abstract: Nine-year-old Walter Verfelt and his brother Chester, aged 6, live at 352 Fifty-ninth Street, South Brooklyn. abstract: The Hamburg-American liner Pretoria came in on Thursday night with some 400 cabin passengers. abstract: LONDON, Sept. 8. -- To use a popular expression, New York is giving the London money and stock markets "beans," borrowing London's cash, cutting down the Bank of England's laboriously built up gold reserve, and raiding the bullion market. abstract: PUTNEY, England, Sept. 8. -- Cambridge defeated Harvard to-day in the International boat race on the Thames by a trifle over two lengths. She won rowing perfectly and well within her strength. The time was fast, 0:19:16, 29 seconds behind the record for the course. The Light Blue crew, however, seemed capable of even better time, and won by stalling off Harvard's desperate spurts, stroke for stroke, and rowing evenly between times.

abstract: CHICAGO, Sept. 9. -- Chicago won the fourth straight game from Pittsburg to-day. It was a light hitting and rather loose fielding game. abstract: PITTSBURG, Sept. 11. -- The most remarkable baseball game ever seen in Pittsburg was played to-day between the Plttsburg and Cincinnati teams. The game lasted fifteen innings and neither side was able to score. The longest game previously played here was of fourteen innings, and this feat was accomplished only twice, in 1SS7 with the Philadelphias, and in 1904 in a post-season game with the Cleveland American League team.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 11. -- The cruiser Des Moines, which sailed from Norfolk yesterday, is going to Cuba. This is not stated officially, but is known to be the case. It is said that she is going there to protect American interests, but it is known that her mission involves more than that. She is to take President Palma off the island in case the situation there becomes desperate.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Sept. 13. -- The Pittsburg team won both games of a double-header from Cincinnati to-day. It scored five runs in the first inning of the first game and was never headed. abstract: CINCINNATI, Sept. 13. -- William Jennings Bryan of Nebraska and Tom L. Johnson of Cleveland have had their craniums read by a Cincinnati phrenologist. abstract: William K. Vanderbilt, Jr., set the pace yesterday morning for the racing autoists on Long Island during the high speed practice hours over the Vanderbilt Cup course. abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 16. -- The announcement from Havana that the Government has declared an armistice was expected here. If it is true, as reported from Havana, that the Government's design is to arrange peace before Mr. Taft gets there the conclusion drawn here is that the Palma administration is willing to go to any length rather than make the full state of things in Cuba known to the American Government.

abstract: CHICAGO, Sept. 21. -- There were two bumps end a crash at the South Side baseball grounds to-day. abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 22. -- Brig. Gen. Funston left Washington this afternoon for Tampa, whence he will sail for Havana. Reports of disturbances are coming to the police every few minutes.

abstract: On the North German Lloyd liner Koenig Albert, in late Wednesday night from Naples via Gibraltar, arrived Herr and Frau Essipoff. The woman, according to stories told by the custom officers, was the eloping wife of an officer of the Russian Army. The Koenig Albert docked early yesterday morning, and when she did Robert Watchorn, Commissioner of Immigration at this port, and M. Lodygensky, the Russian Consul General at New York, were on the pier.

abstract: Yom Kippur, or the Day of Atonement, the most important day in the Jewish calendar and the one most generally observed by the Hebrews, will begin at sunset this evening, and will continue until the first stars appear in the heavens tomorrow evening. It is the tenth day of the month Tishri, the first month in the new year, and marks the end of the penitential period which began with the celebration of Rosh Hashanah.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 27. -- Two features of the day's developments with regard to the Cuban situation have special significance. First, the War Department permitted to become known the composition of the detail of troops to compose the first expedition to be sent to Cuba as soon as the order for intervention comes. Second, Secretary Taft telegraphed orders for Col. E.H. Crowder of the Judge Advocate's Corps to proceed to Havana at once.

abstract: The extreme susceptibility of the average Wall Street mind to the influence of fluctuations was illustrated yesterday in a very striking manner.
